 7 Apr 2022 02:23:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-05-25"}
{"id":"2204.03165","submitter":"Alberto Nocera","authors":"Alberto Nocera, Gonzalo Alvarez","title":"Root-N Krylov-space correction-vectors for spectral functions with the\n  density matrix renormalization group","comments":"11 pages, 5 figures, Supplementary Material","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.106.205106","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el cond-mat.supr-con","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We propose a method to compute spectral functions of generic Hamiltonians\nusing the density matrix renormalization group (DMRG) algorithm directly in the\nfrequency domain, based on a modified Krylov space decomposition to compute the\ncorrection-vectors. Our approach entails the calculation of the root-N (N=2 is\nthe standard square root) of the Hamiltonian propagator using Krylov space\ndecomposition, and repeating this procedure N times to obtain the actual\ncorrection-vector. We show that our method greatly alleviates the burden of\nkeeping a large bond dimension at large target frequencies, a problem found\nwith conventional correction-vector DMRG, while achieving better computational\nperformance at large N. We apply our method to spin and charge spectral\nfunctions of t-J and Hubbard models in the challenging two-leg ladder geometry,\nand provide evidence that the root-N approach reaches a much improved\nresolution compared to conventional correction-vector.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 7 Apr 2022 02:31:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-11-23"}
